Top Culprit Putin
Moscow—German, French and Swedish medical experts have unanimously stated that Alexei Navalny is a victim of the nerve agent Novichok. Navalny is the biggest opponent of Russian President Putin and also the founder of the Anti-Corruption Foundation.
Fortunately, because Navalny survived, the relationship between Russia and Germany has not deteriorated.
In order to demonstrate her "clear stance," German Chancellor Merkel declared that Navalny is "a victim persecuted for freedom of speech."
In her view, this incident is very serious, and only the Russian government can and must respond to it.
She emphasized that the entire world needs an explanation.
Merkel called on Russian authorities to conduct an independent and transparent investigation.
The EU and the UK also supported this call.
If the investigation proves that the Russian government is the culprit behind the incident, the European Commission will impose a new round of sanctions.
Regardless of that, according to the provisions of the Chemical Weapons Convention, poisoning is a prohibited act.
This is not the first time the Putin government has used the nerve agent Novichok against its political opponents.
In 2018, former Russian double agent Sergei Skripal and his daughter Yulia were poisoned on British soil.
Both survived and went into hiding.
The Kremlin strongly denied both incidents.
Regarding the Navalny incident, Kremlin spokesperson Dmitry Peskov insisted, "There is no evidence to blame the Russian government."
The head of Russia's Foreign Intelligence Service, Sergei Naryshkin, even claimed that it was the act of Western intelligence agencies, attempting to tarnish the reputation of the Russian government.
Naryshkin's statement is obviously an excuse, but he also revealed a fact: the Navalny incident is more harmful than beneficial to Russia.
Poisoning a well-known political opponent just before upcoming elections, and using a nerve agent developed by the former Soviet Union, is simply indefensible.
Especially considering that the people of neighboring Belarus are currently protesting against the August elections, this timing is particularly intriguing.
Moreover, the Kremlin's initial response to the Navalny incident was especially confusing.
Shouldn't the Russian government have planned more carefully before committing the crime?
If, as Germany claims, it was indeed the Russian government that did it, then this murder was also a failed operation.
Putin has always been the Darth Vader of the international political arena (the top villain in the movie "Star Wars"), intervening in the US election, inciting street protests in France, luring the UK to leave the EU, and propping up Bashar al-Assad in Syria.
As a former KGB agent, he is shrewd, far-sighted, and cunning.
Then why couldn't he kill Skripal and Navalny?
Why could Navalny escape to Germany and be quickly diagnosed as having been poisoned?
Now, Putin is facing international condemnation and sanctions, and the second phase of the Nord Stream gas pipeline project to Germany is at risk of cancellation.
This assassination clearly was a lose-lose situation.
In fact, it has further fueled public outrage against the Russian authorities' misconduct.
Even if it was not Putin who did it, blaming Western intelligence agencies is even more outrageous.
If such accusations are true, scientists from Germany and Sweden would not have revealed the fact that the nerve agent Novichok was used.
It is more likely a conspiracy planned by Putin's political inner circle.
Perhaps Putin wanted Navalny to be quiet before the election, or perhaps it was due to Navalny's anti-corruption investigation.
In Russia, you can buy various products and services on the black market, including military-grade nerve agents.
Putin's political enforcers, though loyal, are very foolish; they thought poisoning Navalny was a good idea, and only a few people involved know the truth.
Other failed poisoning attempts have similar characteristics: the poisoning of journalist Vladimir Kara-Murza in 2015 and 2017. Kara-Murza was the coordinator of the Khodorkovsky Public Inquiry Commission.
The poisoning of Peter Pevtsov, the publisher of the independent news website Mediazona, in 2018.
Mediazona is a website that reports on abuses of power within the Russian judiciary.
Going further back, we can trace it to 2006, when former KGB officer Alexander Litvinenko was poisoned. Alexander Litvinenko frequently criticized Russian security agencies.
Just like the Navalny incident, such poisonings often backfire.
In 2004, Anna Politkovskaya, a liberal columnist for the newspaper Novaya Gazeta, was poisoned on a plane flying from Moscow to Beslan. Although she survived, she was shot dead in the elevator of her apartment two years later.
As Putin said, her death caused tremendous damage to the image of the Russian government.
This does not in any way excuse the Kremlin.
Whether or not Putin personally ordered it, the system he created allows such crimes to occur. This system is both inefficient and useless, a farce involving shameless actors.
Navalny's death is the result the Kremlin wanted, and satisfying the master, Putin, is the ultimate goal of the henchmen.
Within Putin's inner circle, loyalty is the only goal.
Even if the poisoning failed, they would not be punished.
Because they did it for the president's benefit.
Those who want to find evidence of the poisoning may be disappointed.
Regardless of that, the Kremlin is the culprit.
Western countries must clearly express their stance, and impose sanctions on Russia even if it affects their own economies.
Putin has created a system centered around himself.
All responsibilities that occur in Russia are attributable to him.
